Chapter One
Kolen
Itania time, 4:30 a.m. Kolen hated getting up so early. Mainly because he was responsible for waking up the rest of the platoon. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat suit, slipped on his assault vest, packed up his things from the cabinet, and carefully picked up a small special box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks, his boots crunching on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a light puff and then opened the door. Over the past week, he had to think of every possible way to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, because half the time it didn't go off, and all that could be heard from the speaker was a faint hiss.
"Time to wake them up?" Kolen turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemich approaching.
"Yes." Kolen replied.
"What method are you going to use this time?"
Kolen hadn't even had time to answer when the door opened, and Harris, Cress, and a few others rushed out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Cress said.
"What woke you up?" Kolen asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use today to wake everyone up. Second, the first squad to get up can have priority for breakfast," a soldier named Ravek replied. "You know how bad that breakfast is."
Kolen said, "You're right, Ravek corporal." He reached out and pressed the switch. The barracks immediately filled with a刺耳 alarm sound. He heard people shouting inside, accompanied by a rush of confused footsteps.
"My goodness, Valturi," Nemich said. "I thought by now they should have learned to get up with you."
"My brothers from basic training did," Kolen pointed to Harris, Cres, and Ravek. "But to be fair, their platoon leader and company commander knew to get up before the soldiers did."
A few seconds later, the rest of the platoon ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new soldiers looked sleepy, while others looked very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Kollen said cheerfully.
"Excuse me, sir, why did you wake us up in that way?" asked a squad member (sergeant).
"Because those ordinary alarm clocks are just junk. And Daybreak never sleeps in." Kollen said.
"Take your personal belongings," Kollen continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the company, he was responsible for assisting Captain Boradin Xiao, the company commander, in supervising and leading the company. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and lieutenants, give you and your troops 15 minutes to do a final check and bring along the rations needed for today."
The members of the Exodus company quickly dispersed. They were part of the 2nd Shock Division of the 2nd Army Group. Before the merger, they were originally two separate companies, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite company, and Kollen felt a complex mix of emotions about his promotion to lieutenant, for there were many reasons behind it.
Kolen and First Squad Lieutenant Nemicz walked side by side along the brightly lit path of the base, where the lights on both sides were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which helped them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had begun using "Wildcat" tactics in both the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for the Hellbreakers," Nemicz said with a dry smile. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"Some frontline base outside Ianlos City. We're being sent to support the ground assault," Kolen said, taking a puff of his cigarette. He somewhat blamed Kres for getting him addicted to smoking, but thinking about the past year, which had been filled with countless battles, he let it go, so he said nothing.
"That's terrible. The frontline is really under pressure," Nemicz said softly. "All the news coming out of here is 'Support the war, aid the Kurgan frontline,' why isn't there any support for the Holan frontline?"
"Well said, brother," Kolen said, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll be going with the First Armor Platoon, no walking involved. Captain Xiao should be there."
"Captain Xiao let us ride along?" Nemyts asked, somewhat surprised.
"Yes. Honestly, he isn't as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not annoying either."
Kolen raised his thumb and index finger to press the microphone at his throat, while shifting his backpack to his back. "Exodus company, all units, assemble at the western vehicle yard after completing your tasks. We will depart at 05:00 along with the First Armor Platoon."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Kres, and Raviq were all lower-ranking sergeants. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had always been good friends. Kolen felt like he had known them for a long time, even though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since last week, when the former platoon leader was hit by a Daybreak sniper and retired due to injury, Kres had started leading the second squad.
As they approached the vehicle yard, Kolen and Nemyts looked at about eight Kronos main battle tanks and four Sisk装甲 vehicles. Crew members were running around, ensuring their war machines were in good condition. Kolen quickly spotted Captain Boradin Xiao in the crowd, who was talking with the commander of the armor platoon. As they approached, Captain Xiao glanced at them and came forward, his usually expressionless face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemich... Lieutenant Valturi..." he said, Kolen slowed his steps, Captain Xiao looked at Kolen's holstered pistol and then looked up. "Should the platoon be ready by now?"
